A panchromatic filter (400-900 nm) provides the highest signal-to-noise images, while three band-pass filters (with central wavelengths at 550, 750, and 880 nm and with 40-nm bandwidth) allow the acquisition of color images. The filters are deposited directly on the detector window, in four strips separated by stripes of an absorbing mask which prevents ghosts and well separates different filter areas on the detector. Typical integration times constrained by the S/C motion (i.e., to avoid smearing) are between 0.5 and 7 ms, depending on the position along the orbit and on the filter used. Table 2 summarizes the measured filter characteristics, depending on the observation geometry. The results are very close to specifications. Table 2
